### Do-While Loop

The `do-while` loop is similar to `while`, but it guarantees the code block executes at least once before the condition is tested.

---

### Basic Syntax

```cpp
do {
  // Code to repeat
} while (condition);
```

---

### Example

```cpp
int i = 0;
do {
  cout << i << " ";
  i++;
} while (i < 5);
// Output: 0 1 2 3 4
```

---

### Guaranteed First Execution

```cpp
int password;
do {
  cout << "Enter password: ";
  cin >> password;
} while (password != 1234);
```

---

### While vs Do-While

| Aspect | `while` | `do-while` |
|--------|---------|------------|
| Condition check | Before first iteration | After first iteration |
| Minimum executions | 0 | 1 |
| Common use | Counter loops | Menu input, validation |
| Syntax | `while (cond) { }` | `do { } while (cond);` |

---

### Edge Case Example

```cpp
int x = 10;
while (x < 5) {        // Never executes
  cout << "while: " << x;
}

do {
  cout << "do-while: " << x;  // Executes once
} while (x < 5);
```

---

> **Key Point:** Use `do-while` when the loop body must execute at least once regardless of the condition (e.g., menu prompts, input validation).

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  int number;

  do {
    cout << "Enter a positive number: ";
    cin >> number;
  } while (number <= 0);

  cout << "You entered: " << number << endl;
  return 0;
}
